<br>
Anyway, I haven't even seen the board in the past year, and as such, the existence of the &quot;Literary Posts&quot; board totally escaped me. Pardon me for being an actor, but isn't this a LARP? A &quot;Live-Action&quot; Role Playing Game, as opposed to . . . say . . . an online RPG, where people post expository narratives and these are taken as the meat of the experience?<br>
<br>
Don't get me wrong, I like the idea of downtime, and encourage any type of expression that will add to the LARP experience, but I do have a few problems with what I have seen of the board, the most prominent being the posting of character histories. Honestly, if a person can't figure out enough of your character history by talking to your character, perhaps you should work on finding a character that you can more accurately portray (translation: this, as a LARP, is a game of acting, please feel free to do so). I barely know the &quot;character histories&quot; of many of my closest friends, and I'm going to be one of their bridesmaids!!! In short, I think posting character histories is undermining the LARP experience, even though it may flesh out the character and be a phenomonal piece of writing.<br>
<br>
I would like to clarify that I think many parts of a LARP should be in writing, and that online exposition is a great way to conduct downtime, in fact I plan to post the framework of the opera (that is, the parts that were not the RP) as it pertains to many players and is relevant to the game, however I would never give other players my character history for two reasons: A) in a game of intrigue, mystery, suspense and paranoia are tools of the narrative, whereas understanding and trust are counterproductive to successfully executing that narrative and B) Other players have no reason to know, what's more, if I were to encourage that much RP via written exposition, I would be afraid that so little of what was written would be incorporated into the weekly performances of the characters because it was already expressed through writing.<br>
<br>
I don't expect the forum to close, and I'm not writing an indictment of all the posts there already. I understand that we all process things such as this game differently and wish to bring up some considerations when posting, rather than stop the creative process. In short, I feel there is some information better learned in character through interaction, both from the perspective of having more fun discovering things, and from the perspective that forcing players to express and read more into our performances will heighten the Live Action gaming experience.<br>
<br>
I suppose at some point I could have included something about my opinion being humble, but it isn't and I don't really have a problem with that. If I state my opinion as fact (and I most certainly will in the future if I haven't already) and a particularly reader thinks I am citing fact, they are incorrect and I take no responsibility for inability to recognize opinion.<br>
<br>
I do like my opinions though.<br>
<br>
And one-sentence paragraphs.<br>
<br>
Sentence framents, too.<br>
<br>
For your consideration,<br>
Brandon Schmidt<br>
<br>
PS. Some might react to this post by recommending I simply don't read the Literary section, or ignore the ones I don't want to read and get over it. I plan to do just that, but wanted to put forth my opinion in a way that might be a useful model to consider. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F9FBFD><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bscbnforum58570.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stephencrowley>Stephen Crowley</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#FF9300>(2/1/03 10:20:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fscbnforum58570frm16.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: NOT ABOUT DRAMA (well . . .kinda, but not colloquially)</span><hr size=1> Brandon,<br>
